{"ts": "2026-06-09T16:35:24.699096+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "I have all the evidence I need from the `package.json` and the repository file listing. Here's the answer:\n\n---\n\n## Contributors are expected to use **pnpm**; npm is **not** acceptable.\n\nThere are three strong, converging signals in the repository:\n\n### 1. `packageManager` field in `package.json`\n```json\n\"packageManager\": \"pnpm@10.20.0\"\n```\nThis is the [Corepack `packageManager` specification](https://nodejs.org/api/packages.html#packagemanager). It tells Node.js's built-in Corepack tooling to automatically download and use **pnpm 10.20.0** when a contributor runs any package-manager command in this repo. If a contributor has Corepack enabled and runs `npm install`, Corepack will intercept the call and switch to pnpm.\n\n### 2. Preinstall script that blocks non-pnpm usage\n```json\n\"preinstall\": \"npx only-allow pnpm\"\n```\nThe [`only-allow`](https://github.com/nicolo-ribaudo/only-allow) package is a hard guard. If someone runs `npm install` or `yarn install`, the preinstall hook fires, detects the wrong package manager, and **aborts the install with an error message** telling the user to use pnpm instead.\n\n### 3. Lock file is `pnpm-lock.yaml`\nThe repository commits a `pnpm-lock.yaml` file (207 KB). There is no `package-lock.json` (npm) or `yarn.lock`. This means only pnpm can read the committed lockfile and produce deterministic installs.\n\n### Bottom line\nThe combination of the Corepack `packageManager` field, the `only-allow` preinstall guard, and the presence of a pnpm-specific lockfile means **pnpm is mandatory** for this project. Attempting to use npm will be actively blocked at install time.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 598, "prompt_tokens": 9613, "total_tokens": 10211, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": nul